'''Kalawan''' (originally meaning "The caves") is the name of an archaeological site in the area of [[Taxila]] in Pakistan, where it is one of the largest Buddhist establishment.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Khan|first1=Muhammad Ishtiaq|title=World heritage: sites in Pakistan|date=2000|publisher=UNESCO|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7xZuAAAAMAAJ|language=en}}</ref> It is located about 2km from the [[Dharmarajika]] stupa.<ref name="Marshall 129">{{cite book|last1=Marshall|first1=John|title=A Guide to Taxila|date=2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107615441|page=129ff|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JEMbH2aDO0UC&pg=PA129|language=en}}</ref>

Kalawan has a [[vihara]] monastery, which is the largest in northern India. An inscription, recording the enshrinement of relics as a gift to the [[Sarvastivadin]] School, was found in a [[chaitya]] hall mentioning the date of "the 134th year of [[Azes I|Azes]]," which corresponds to 77 CE.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hirakawa|first1=Akira|title=A History of Indian Buddhism: From Śākyamuni to Early Mahāyāna|date=1993|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|isbn=9788120809550|page=233|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XjjwjC7rcOYC&pg=PA233|language=en}}</ref>

Small stupas were found inside the monasteries.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schopen|first1=Gregory|title=Bones, Stones, and Buddhist Monks: Collected Papers on the Archaeology, Epigraphy, and Texts of Monastic Buddhism in India|date=1997|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=9780824818708|page=185|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxdZ-BVNm_IC&pg=PA185|language=en}}</ref> The Kalawan monastery, together with the [[Dharmarajika]] display an original kind of architectural arrangement in which an image shrine is built opposite the entrance.<ref name="Behrendt 170">{{cite book|last1=Behrendt|first1=Kurt A.|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik|date=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004135952|page=170|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9_vbgkzUSkC&pg=PA170|language=en}}</ref> It is thought that this architectural pattern was initiated in the northwest and then became the prototype for the later development of monasteries with shrines in [[Devnimori]], [[Ajanta Caves|Ajanta]], [[Aurangabad, Maharashtra|Aurangabad]], [[Ellora]], [[Nalanda]], [[Ratnagiri]] and others.<ref name="Behrendt 170"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Behrendt|first1=Kurt A.|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik|date=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004135952|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C9_vbgkzUSkC&pg=PA171|language=en}}</ref> 
