{{short description|Etruscan god of the sky}} {{for|the immunological technique TINIA |Turbidimetric inhibition immunoassay}} {{Infobox deity | type = Etruscan | name = Tinia | image = File:Tinia Staatliche Antikensammlungen, München, 2013.jpg | caption = Terracotta bust of Tinia from 300–250 {{small|{{abbr|BCE|Before Common Era}}}} | deity_of = [[sky god|God of the Sky]] | abode = | symbol = [[Thunderbolt]], [[eagle]], [[ivy]] wreath | consort = [[Thalna]] or [[Uni (mythology)|Uni]] | parents = | siblings = | children = [[Hercle]] and [[Menrva]] | mount = | Greek_equivalent = [[Zeus]] | Roman_equivalent = [[Jupiter (god)|Jupiter]] | equivalent1_type = Egypt | equivalent1=[[Amun]] }} [[File:Populonia AR 5 asses 700006.jpg|thumb|253px|'''Tinia''' on a [[As (Roman coin)|Roman As]] from [[Etruria]]]] '''Tinia''' (also '''Tin''', '''Tinh''', '''Tins''' or ''Tina'') was the god of the [[sky]] and the highest god in [[Etruscan mythology]], equivalent to the [[Roman mythology|Roman]] [[Jupiter (god)|Jupiter]] and the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[Zeus]].<ref>de Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth, Sacred History and Legend'', page 53</ref> He was the husband of [[Thalna]] or [[Uni (mythology)|Uni]] and the father of [[Hercle]].
The [[Etruscans]] believed in Nine Great Gods, who had the power of hurling thunderbolts; they were called ''Novensiles'' by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]].<ref name=ECC>{{cite book|title=The cities and cemeteries of Etruria: Vol.I |first=George |last=Dennis |year=1848 |place=London}}</ref> Of thunderbolts there were eleven sorts, of which Tinia, as the supreme thunder-god, wielded three.<ref name=ECC/> Tinia was also part of the powerful "trinity" that included [[Menrva]] and Uni, and had temples in every city of [[Etruria]].<ref name=JAG>{{cite book|title=The Gentile and the Jew: Vol.II |first=Johann Joseph Ignaz |last=von Döllinger |year=1862 |place=London}}</ref> Tinia was sometimes represented as seated and with a beard or sometimes standing and beardless.<ref name=JAG/> In terms of [[symbol]]ism, Tinia has the [[thunderbolt]] and the rod of power, and is generally accompanied by the [[eagle]] and sometimes has a [[Ivy|wreath of ivy]] round his head, in addition to the other insignia of [[Jove]].
Some of Tinia's possible [[epithet]]s are detailed on the [[Haruspex|Piacenza Liver]], a bronze model of a liver used for [[haruspicy]]. These inscriptions have been transcribed as ''Tin Cilens'', ''Tin Θuf'' and ''Tinś Θne''. There have been a number of suggestions as to their meaning, but the [[Etruscan language]] is poorly understood and there is no scholarly consensus for the translation.
==Inscriptions== {{multiple image | direction = vertical | width = 200 | footer = | image1 = Chimera d'arezzo, fi, 03.JPG | alt1 = | caption1 = [[Chimera of Arezzo]] | image2 = Chimera d'arezzo, firenze, 05 firma.JPG | alt2 = | caption2 = ''Tinia'' inscription on foreleg }}
Tinia appears in several inscriptions, including: * [[Kylix (drinking cup)|Kylix]] painted by [[Oltos]] (ca 500 BC): :'''Itun turuce venel atelinas Tinas cliniiaras.''' :This has given Venel Atelinas for the sons of Tin (ie: The [[Dioscuri]]<ref name=TDT>{{cite book|title=The Etruscan language: an introduction |last=Giuliano Bonfante and Larissa Bonfante |year=1983 |place=Manchester University Press}}</ref>)
*On the bronze [[Chimera of Arezzo]]: :'''Tinscvil''' :A gift to Tinia
